<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1437,152,838]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,320,654,680]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Remarks:</emphasis>
Only males have been collected from 
<taxonomicName box="[774,1003,655,680]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scylla">
<emphasis box="[774,1003,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Hemipenthes scylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Externally it is distinguished by the reduced pigmentation of wing, limited to the base and anterior margin of wing, like in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<taxonomicName box="[1180,1283,693,718]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albus">H. albus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1295,1431,693,718]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lepidota">H. lepidota</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[151,322,732,757]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="translucens">H. translucens</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, and 
<taxonomicName box="[387,517,732,757]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="webberi">
<emphasis box="[387,517,732,757]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">H. webberi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but in contrast with these species 
<taxonomicName box="[928,1032,732,757]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scylla">
<emphasis box="[928,1032,732,757]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">H. scylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has characteristic pigmentation in cell 
<emphasis box="[204,215,770,795]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">r</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[216,224,786,800]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<number box="[216,224,786,800]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" value="1.0">1</number>
</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[241,481,770,795]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scylla">
<emphasis box="[241,481,770,795]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Hemipenthes scylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a common species and has been reported as territorial (
<bibRefCitation author="Avalos-Hernandez" pageId="36" pageNumber="48" refString="Avalos-Hernandez, O. (2007) Bombyliidae (Insecta: Diptera) de Quilamula en el area de reserva Sierra de Huautla, Morelos, Mexico. Acta Zoologica Mexicana (n. s.), 23, 139 - 169." type="journal article" year="2007">
Ávalos-Hernández, 
<number box="[151,215,812,838]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" value="2007.0">2007</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). It is distributed throughout 
<collectingCountry box="[554,643,812,838]" name="Mexico" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Mexico</collectingCountry>
having its most northern limit in Arizona and Texas.
</paragraph>
